The Prague Stock Exchange plunges into negative territory against the close of business.
After the steep waste in the morning, the Prague Stock Exchange was able to correct the losses.
Transactions with ČEZ's shares reached almost half of normal day-to-day trading.
The Prague Stock Exchange continued Monday's slump at the start of Tuesday's operations, when it fell by another six percentage points.
This time, the reason for the slump was on Wall Street.
In the Czech Republic, too, the market’s response to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which had refused to support a stabilization plan for the financial sector there, is thus evident.
Case of shares in Asia
Shares in the Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic case on Tuesday, although the indices were able to make up for some of the losses during the course of the day.
The Hang Seng Stock Exchange index lost nearly four percentage points over the course of the business day, but was later able to make up for some of the losses, thus reducing the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index, which monitors the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell 3.8 percent, while in Shanghai, markets were closed.
Shares on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent but then reduced losses to 4.3 percent.
The stock market in Taiwan fell 3.6 percent, according to the index there.
"The timing for the bailout in the U.S. is uncertain and will affect financial markets worldwide," Hong Kong chief executive Joseph Yam said in a statement.
Hong Kong, although it belongs to China, determines its own monetary policy, that is, regardless of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as those in the United States.
American lawmakers should return to the negotiating table as soon as possible, according to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, and pass the draft support for the financial system.
Otherwise, it threatens that other countries would also be affected by the slump.
A bloodbath of American stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected the plan for support for the financial system, for which up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 trillion Kč) should be spent.
Lawmakers thus ignored President George Bush's request to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and thus help stabilize the entire economy.
American stocks experienced a bloodbath on Monday, and major stock indices saw the biggest slump in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, a similar slump it had last recorded in 1987.
The index had already fallen before the vote, but there were hardly any signs that the draft would not get through in the House of Representatives, the index experienced a free fall.
Congress makes concession: U.S. government may pump 700 billion dollars into banks
The top representatives of the American Congress and the administration of President George W. Bush has agreed on a broader form of a deal on financial assistance to the American financial system.
It is due to be voted on early next week.
American lawmakers made a breakthrough in talks on the passage of a rescue plan in the form of financial assistance to the American financial system amounting to 700 billion dollars (about 12 trillion crowns).
However, this does not mean a victory.
Congressmen have yet to negotiate some details of the agreement before they are allowed to publish and vote on the final version of the law.
The plan to support the financial system will be negotiated in the U.S. Congress on Monday.
On Sunday, the chairman of the Committee on Banking and Financial Services told Reuters.
In the Senate, according to different data, the plan could probably be voted on on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, a notice that the plan will be adopted should be the first significant psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
After that, however, there is a "disillusionment" due to the complicated mechanisms, as could be helped in the markets in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made significant progress.
We have clarified our differing views on what a package to stabilize the market should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her words, there could still be a final vote on Sunday.
Representatives of lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson on the night of Sunday to give the government fund its final form.
This provides for a purchase of unsellable mortgage assets from the financial companies, which plunge the financial firms into heavy losses and endanger the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
You have to continue the recovery plan, but I think we are at our destination," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian business
The global financial crisis is also clearly reflected in the stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to the words of the Democratic Senator of Nevada, Harry Reid, the lawmakers are trying to reach a final agreement before Sunday in Congress.
This is to reassure investors before doing business in the Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where a decision of the Congress could influence the business on Monday.
But it is not yet clear when both chambers of the American Congress will vote on the law, but there is also uncertainty about whether the negotiations at the last minute could not fail on a problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be passed in the next few days.
But the law will still undergo some changes.
The total amount intended to help the system should be divided into two parts.
The initial 350 billion dollars is to be provided as soon as possible, as President George Bush called for.
But Congress can block the distribution of the remaining money if it has the impression that the program does not fulfil its function, at another 100 billion dollars and later the final 350 billion dollars.
Bush positively evaluates progress in negotiations
The president has veto power in this decision, but Congress can overrule his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program has remained, which was based on gaining finance for buying off bad mortgage securities whose value has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are no longer able to repay their mortgages.
"We worked it all out.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, the Senate then on Monday," according to Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
The American President Bush was also satisfied with the progress.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and "assesses the mutual effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Restriction of golden parachutes
The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee Christopher Dodd, the senior negotiator, said that lawmakers had agreed on a responsibility for the money program, the protection of taxpayers from losses, the completion of perks and a timetable for financing the plan.
The new law is also intended to restrict the so-called golden parachutes for directors of the companies involved in the programme and shall set up a committee to which supervision of the fund is to be held.
This is to be headed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard and made a major advance towards an agreement that works and is important for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also anticipates help for homeowners who have trouble repaying their mortgage.
The government should negotiate new rates on mortgages it buys up, with the goal of cutting the monthly cost to the debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological Help
The proposed plan is a good idea, according to the main economist of Patria Finance David Marek, but implementation will be very difficult.
"This is because you do not know by what mechanism and at what price the problematic assets are bought up.
That will be crucial to how the financial sector and the government split the losses among themselves," Marek told the iHNed.cz server this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now or early next week is not decisive, according to Marek.
"Much more important is that congressmen agree to support the plan and that they say goodbye to it as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement on the fact that it comes to a farewell is the most important thing at this moment," Marek stressed.
Triumph of the right-wing populists in Austria, overall they come to 29 percent
A noticeable weakening of both parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties brought after the first preliminary results the early parliamentary elections of Sunday in Austria.
The Austrian People’s Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, where the position of the previous chairman Wilhelm Molterer is seriously on the verge.
In contrast, the election director of the alliance for the future of Austria (BZÖ), the Carinthian state governor Jörg Haider, is gearing up for a triumphant return to federal politics.
According to the results so far, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest force in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but compared to the last elections in 2006, it loses 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP scored even worse, which loses almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results of these two major parties in Austrian post-war history, and especially with the People's Party, which had demanded the early elections, this is a truly catastrophic result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP had withdrawn from the coalition, the People's Party had a clear advantage over the SPÖ.
Voters, however, have probably punished the party for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about a possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be the case as early as Monday at an extraordinary meeting of the party's executive board.
Such a development would probably pave the way to the most likely way out of the election debacle, i.e. to a renewal of the grand coalition of the SPÖ and ÖVP.
In view of the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Liberals (FPÖ) provisionally received 18 percent, the BZÖ eleven percent of the votes - but at the same time expressed their fear that the year 1999 could be repeated when the People's Party had made agreements with the populists (at that time the FPÖ was still uniform, in 2005 it split from the BZÖ) with regard to a joint government, which had even imposed sanctions on the part of the European Union
Jörg Haider, who has already stated that he is ready to cooperate with each party, is obviously counting on this development and expects to return to Vienna in Austrian federal policy.
The Green Party also entered the parliament, but it suffered slight losses and slipped from third to fifth place among the Austrian political parties.
No other party has probably mastered the four percent hurdle and therefore did not move into parliament.
Duel on knife's edge: MP3 player against mobile phones.
We advise you on your choice
While almost every phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls yet.
Therefore, of course, it looks like it is better to buy only one phone.
In spite of everything, there are enough reasons why you should get a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the type of use and the claims of the future owner.
I'm sure you'll hardly buy a great expensive turntable for home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album.
Once, such musical novelties do not appear on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this either.
However, if you have LPs with art rock, jazz or blues on the shelf, you probably at least dream of one.
So it is also with the music on the road, i.e. with compressed music, in simple terms - music in MP3 format.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may not be acceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, but a Pink Floyd fan will hardly be able to handle headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The selection is wide-ranging.
The life of the batteries is also crucial.
Some good music players can play much more than just music, but what phones can do don't even make them happy.
No modern device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, the phone and the texting, it can play music and videos, record both, it has a better, sometimes a worse camera and may also be able to navigate.
And if you still include the smartphones and communicators, you almost have a small computer in your pocket.
It is a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and not photograph a TV.
But the universality of mobile phones also has disadvantages.
However, the more features you use on your phone, the more often you will need to reload it.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy guzzlers.
Only a few mobile phones can play music for more than ten-twelve hours, usually it is much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the simplest) are significantly more powerful.
That’s why you should expect cheap phones to be able to play music for more than a few hours.
If you still make a phone call from time to time, you prefer to buy a charger for the office for safety - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the less good ones can withstand at least 9 hours of continuous operation with one time charging.
Another problem is if you want to transfer the music to your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a small part of the devices has a USB end, in addition, not every mobile phone can be connected directly to a PC without special software.
Of course, you can overplay the music directly to a storage medium, but only a few card readers can be finished without reduction with the tiny memory cards that are used in mobile phones.
With exceptions (iPod), you do not need any special software for players.
You only need to feed the device from your PC via USB port with music.
Most mobile phones and players create a music library themselves, ordered by the name of the artist, the title of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating by users.
Some devices only map the tree structure of the address directory, similar to Windows Explorer, some can do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobile phones can do more
When choosing a specific device, you should inquire in particular about the service life of the battery, the storage capacity, the quality and the type of sound and of course also the ease of use.
If music is above all a backdrop for you and you only listen to it every day, for example in the tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 files is enough.
Which can really be almost any phone.
You also don’t have to control which music formats a mobile phone or a player can process.
MP3 will all create, and most of the music you get will be in this format right now.
The format is one of the most common, and most devices can also play music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (a format that Apple and its iPods use).
Better phones also allow the purchase of music online.
You only have to access the corresponding pages of a provider (or another provider) via mobile Internet, and you can buy a song or album.
This service can already be a striking argument in itself for why you should get a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of the providers is bad and is usually limited to fast radio hits.
Prices are not the lowest either.
In general, however, it is assumed that this type of sale of music (whether it will be via GSM, Internet or wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry the mobile phone with them.
If you feel like listening to something, reach for the phone in your jacket pocket while the player is lying at home forgotten.
However, it depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least a wireless hands-free device.
If not, you can access the built-in speaker that almost every phone has, but only the fewest MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be in the price for many.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand crowns.
For three and four thousand crowns you already get a very decent Walkman.
The biggest handicap for most will be that there are no regular headphones.
The best and most technically mature phones with a 3.5 mm opening for regular headphones cost up to fifteen thousand crowns.
The advantage of the players is in turn the easy operation.
The easiest - and not necessarily cheapest (see selection) - player can really serve anyone.
A minimum of functions, the similarity in operation with the formerly normal cassette recorder or, for example, the turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of an erroneously employed mobile Internet and a subsequently horrendous invoice for data transmissions.
What device should you use
Also the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. B. Vodafone 527) usually has a slot for replaceable storage media (type M2, microSD &. them.).
Even if you buy a corresponding card, two thousand crowns are enough.
But beware.
The basic models usually only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive can also read 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, then reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to put more than 1100 crowns on the table.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you prefer to take specialized mobile phones - Walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some from Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have standalone control knobs for MP3, and the ease of use thus comes close to that of a single MP3 player.
The furthest here is Sony Ericsson, whose phones from the Walkman series have the same user interface as the individually sold MP3 players.
The same services in the same price category of up to four thousand crowns, but with a higher storage capacity (up to 16 GB) and a long battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours) will provide you with MP3 players from the above-mentioned manufacturers.
The first virtual provider is already coming to the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite mature, the Czech providers offer virtually all services, as they are also offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Still, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic ones to lower prices.
Maybe this one won't be long in coming.
The fact that the Czech mobile operators work among the most expensive in Europe in the first place, we have often reported on Mobil.cz.
By the way, this was also confirmed by the telecommunications authority ČTÚ, which drew attention to the fact that the price of a text message here is higher than in the rest of the European Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the area of regulation of roaming fees, there is likely to be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of the Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks the competition that really makes a battle announcement.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of far more than 100%.
The mobile operators, on the other hand, like to complain that there is extremely much competition in the Czech market.
This is often agreed by the chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ) Pavel Dvořák, who in the past had often stated that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that a classic provider with its own network no longer has a lot of chances (by the way, it would probably hardly find frequencies).
But there is still a possibility - a virtual provider.
Especially the entry of virtual providers into the mobile market brought a significant price reduction, to which the classic mobile operators had to react.
Even before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market in the UK, there were similar voices as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has been shown that there is room for such providers and that they can be truly successful.
By the way, you don’t need to look for examples for long.
In February this we reported on the launch of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to attract more than 100 thousand customers and thus become the fifth largest provider in the country.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is that you can focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much fewer customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost of building, operating and maintaining a mobile network.
In the world, the virtual providers usually profile themselves as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone conversations and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a rather good move to rely on a non-clichéd target group.
This provider is specifically aimed at men.
"Real guys choose Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, the operating company of this virtual provider.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could also gain a foothold in the Czech Republic.
Vodafone press officer Miroslav Čepický also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of services."
In the Czech Republic without chance, the mobile operators think
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile operator conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile king.
"While we are talking about an expansion of this successful project, the negotiations in the Czech Republic are not particularly hopeful.
There will be more of a market entry of Mobilking in other countries of our region," says in a telephone conversation for Mobil.cz Jana Studničková, press officer of the financial group Penta.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic are not particularly inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competitor is created.
The GTS Novera Group, which wants to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers, has been showing their interest in launching a virtual mobile provider for a long time.
"We have a great interest in offering our customers not only fixed-line but also mobile telecom services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly negotiated with all Czech mobile operators about this possibility.
With some of them, we have already been able to achieve negotiation progress," said the press spokesman for the Pavel Kaidl group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
From non-official information, it emerges that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
So far, however, this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this moment, we do not assume that there is room for a full-fledged virtual provider in the Czech Republic.
The Czech market has large specifics compared to other markets.
So far, no subject has approached us with a complex and serious project in this area," says Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2 in his statement for Mobil.cz.
The specifics of the Czech market are also indicated by other providers.
T-Mobile's press secretary Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far, we have not yet found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
And she adds: "On T-Mobile's network, hardly a virtual provider will emerge by the end of the year.
At this moment we would have to have a concrete offer in order to be able to think at such short notice."
Vodafone is more focused on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický comments: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual providers, especially in the area of sharing of costs and infrastructure.
This is precisely what we consider the best from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
The responsible authorities - with the providers hand in hand
The approach of the mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider would mean more competition, this would lead to falling prices and thus also to a decline in profits.
So why should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that the providers can pull together when it comes to something also proves the long back and forth about the emergence of U:fon.
Probably the strongest pressure in the direction of ČTÚ was currently when U:fon was launched, from the company T-Mobile.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTÚ websites.
But now U:fon is just an argument why you should not allow a virtual provider.
Martina Kemrová commented: "The competitive environment of the mobile phone market has also recently been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Taking into account the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new player would place high demands on the market itself and, above all, its services."
However, given this approach by mobile operators, the absolute disinterest of Czech regulators is surprising.
This is not only the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately - in contrast to the UK and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to intervene in economic competition in Czech Republic.
This has only the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
This, however, referred to this entire problem his very typical attitude.
"The entry of a virtual mobile operator would then be possible after a contract between a mobile operator and a virtual provider via the rental of the necessary infrastructure has occurred.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential interested parties was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," said Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS Department of External Relations in his reply to our request.
Such a formulation would not be surprising from representatives of the providers.
From an authority that is to represent consumer interests and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses his position on the market, this is more than questionable.
In particular, when Kristián adds Chalupa: "Abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it can be observed that their entry into the market has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market and a price reduction are probably not among the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is really shocking about this case is the almost touching harmony of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is obvious.
Just as the absolutely same price of petrol at the petrol stations is certainly just coincidence and the result of a fierce competition.
"The Authority has not discovered any signs in this matter that indicate action contrary to competition, and thus it has no reason to intervene in the matter in any way.
None of the providers has a dominant market position, so they do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their actions on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile phone market to virtual providers are also likely to be lacking for the Telecommunications Regulatory Authority," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many contentious points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, elaborated by the ČTÚ, after which telecommunications is a single market from the point of view of economic competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - for the market entry of a virtual provider, the approval of the network operator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator has - logically - the monopoly for its network.
This means that it necessarily assumes a dominant position in a particular segment.
However, even if you do not go along with this argument, it should at least be a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are strikingly similar.
Complaints from a number of interested parties (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) prove that they encounter very similar obstacles in negotiations with all providers.
The transfer of responsibility to the ČTÚ is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distances itself from the whole matter.
This has been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, it has not been possible to promote the extension of the ČTÚ’s competences to the field of economic competition in telecommunications in the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, although a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this all too well, but they probably have other interests.
It's possible when no one is looking
The functioning of some pseudo-virtual providers remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
It is companies that issue their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but which are only partially public.
Normally, they are companies that operate in the field of multilevel marketing.
Own mobile phone services offer, for example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others.
The price lists of these companies usually only reach selected ones.
The joke of the matter is that the company performs opposite the operator as a classic corporate customer who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar resale.
"Should there be any cases you describe, then it may be a violation of the contractual terms that we will then deal with, which can lead to a termination of cooperation with the relevant company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not spread to those responsible for the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, they can be thousands of customers.
However, no operator opposes such a procedure.
From the activities of these companies, they do not have to be neglected profits, at the same time they are - in contrast to the actual virtual providers - not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický draws attention to possible problems: "The law allows such types of speculation, despite everything, the services of these companies are only used by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card in their phone does not run in their name, so they cannot fully have it like the normal customers of the mobile operators."
But that alone should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
Another question opens up for the ÚOHS.
If the mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why lock themselves against a virtual provider?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong competences to uncover such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to be satisfied with the declaration of the providers that they do not know about it and that their terms and conditions would prohibit this.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been emphasized several times in the text, the entry of the market of virtual providers brought with it a significant drop in the price of the various services.
Virtually all countries where virtual providers have emerged have tried to prevent the creation of virtually more or less.
The arguments they used were practically identical - a market that was too small or too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it was precisely at these moments that the regulatory bodies intervened, which by no means tried to safeguard the interests of the mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Be it through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created, and this was followed by more.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves up the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguity in competences is more than favorable in these cases.
But let's not throw the shotgun in the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider soon appears, the Czech mobile market may soon be moving again.
If a provider allows the creation of a virtual mobile carrier, the ÚOHS will not remain idle when it comes to rejecting (discriminating against) other interested parties.
And the Czechs will finally no more more more on the phone than the rest of Europe.
