Wednesday, the 1. October 2008, will go down in the history of Prague transport companies as a date on which the first passengers board a subway, tram or bus carrying an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
These can currently buy about one hundred thousand people who own the chip card Opencard.
Passengers can enjoy a 30-day, 90-day or annual coupon (valued from 1. January 2009) buy and have it played on their chip card at the same time, in the information centres and branches of the transport companies at the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
The coupons are also available via the Internet on the website of the transport companies www.dpp.cz since yesterday.
The service was used by over four hundred customers until the afternoon hours.
Those who use the Internet sale can really forget the output window in the subway stations, where they have had to wait regularly in long lines for their paper tickets.
You buy the coupon via the Internet, which is played on the open card in one of the thirteen branches of the city library.
"At these points, there is also a switch with trained staff available to the travelers, which advises interested parties on the Internet purchase and also plays the coupon on the map," according to the spokesman of the project Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, you can also play the electronic coupons on the open card at self-service machines, which are attached to some subway vestibules.
What do such machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket devaluers, the passengers may already have them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská noticed.
"Currently there are five of them in the city, but by the end of the year it should be eighty," adds Opatrný.
The coupon is controlled by a machine instead of the driver
The operation of the machines, which will work from tomorrow, is easy.
You only have to insert the chip card, and the previously purchased coupon plays itself up.
The electronic coupons will apply from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the surrounding area.
So in the suburban trains and on the bus lines with the numbers 300 to 499, with which mainly the inhabitants from municipalities of the region of Central Bohemia reach the capital.
"In the trains belonging to the Prague integrated traffic, the train attendants have reading devices with which they can check the validity period of the coupons according to time and zone," explains Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid the ticket control. This organization compiles the timetables for the Prague transport companies.
The suburban buses have card readers at the checkout at the driver's.
When boarding, the chip card must not only be presented to the driver, but the open card must be placed at a marked point on the side of the cash register.
The driver thus checks the validity of the coupons played.
"If a passenger wants to check the validity of the coupons played on, nothing is easier than to ask the driver for this information," Drápal said.
A passenger who does not drive with suburban buses and no longer knows when the validity of the coupon will end can in turn go to the self-service machines, where the coupons are played on the card.
Here, the information on the validity of his documents is displayed on the display of the device.
The Sudeten demanded a referendum from the United States
The Sudeten Germans had asked in 1945 for the annexation of the Bohemian Forest to the United States.
This is evident from a letter stored in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we would like to live at least under the auspices of the United States of America.
With such a wish, some groups of Sudeten Germans are said to have turned to the US President in 1945.
This is evident, among other things, from a letter that has been preserved in a private archive and which is now kept in the collections of the South Bohemian Scientific Library.
The Germans of Krumau ask the American president in the letter that he should not allow the return of the "Sudetengau" - which was taken by Hitler on the basis of the Munich agreement - to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation correctly and really want to be sure of the words that the American units are not entering German territory as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads a letter signed with the words "people who care about the fate of the Sudets."
Since the annexation to Czechoslovakia suggests that the Sudeten Germans - in the knowledge of the Czech national character - would expect brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protection of the Bohemian Forest for today and forever.
"We cannot believe that, regardless of the view of a quarter of a million inhabitants, you are giving this area to a foreign state that is oppressing and eliminating minorities, and has contributed nothing to the victory of the Allies," the letter reads.
The reason why the authors cannot sign is allegedly the fear of revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the US President had doubts about the attitude of the Bohemian Forest Germans, it would be sufficient if he initiated a referendum in the Bohemian Forest Gauh about whether the inhabitants wanted to become part of the USA or live under the rule of protection of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may sound somewhat naïve in today’s knowledge of post-war history, it paints a good picture in the opinion of some contemporary witnesses with regard to the expectations of the Sudeten Germans at that time.
Even if the Bohemian Germans at least suspected that one would negotiate about their deportation from the republic, only a few of them even admitted such a possibility.
Some waited for the United States and Britain to negotiate some kind of autonomy for the Sudeten.
Still others believed they could simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
This is also confirmed by the famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, who is from Budweis.
He was in the war as Budweiser German in the Navy on the Baltic Sea.
When he came to British captivity at the end of the war and he was taken to a prisoner-of-war camp in Holstein, dozens more Bohemian Germans came to him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that if they came home, the Czech would suit them," Chalupa said.
None of the German prisoners of war who had lived in Czechoslovakia before the war, reckoned, in his opinion, that he would be expelled from the republic on the basis of the Beneš decrees.
Don't you think - then pay!
An emotionally charged campaign is aimed at motorists
Most expensive action for safety on the streets in Czech history.
This would also be the case in characterising the emotionally charged media campaign that the Ministry of Transport plans to launch on Wednesday.
Minister Aleš Řebíček’s authority expects to dissuade drivers from dangerous behaviour behind the wheel.
The campaign for 150 million crowns will be on TV, on the radio, in the cinema, on the Internet, but also on flyers.
It is intended to dissuade drivers from driving too fast and alcohol at the wheel.
And they also remember to strap on before driving.
The campaign mainly wants to talk to young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians and, last but not least, professional drivers in conscience.
And what is shown in the spots?
Especially stories of people who appeal to emotions.
This is also evidenced by the "bloody" slogan of the whole campaign:
Don't you think - then pay!
The words "don't think" are in capital letters on a license plate.
And in a pool of blood, the word "pay" is written.
This means that you can pay a moment of inattention with your own life.
The spots will "shock" viewers until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where you can see pictures with drastic shots of accident victims.
It is expected that the number of accidents and the number of traffic fatalities on the Czech roads will decrease.
The spots were compiled by the agency Euro RSCG.
Sugar bread and whip for motorists
"For the drivers, the motto is carrot and whip.
Sugar bread means that if they drive at red, for example, they save time.
The whip is then the threat of a penalty or an accident.
The driver must be reminded of the risk," according to the traffic psychologist of the hospital Na Homolce Martin Kořán.
And that is why information campaigns in the press and, above all, negative advertising are necessary, says the psychologist.
In his opinion, even less effective are panels that alert drivers to a danger.
"If you put up a static board that warns of a danger, it will probably soon flow with the environment, and the drivers will no longer notice it," says Kořán.
Olmert would return almost all occupied territories in exchange for peace
The chairman of the provisional Israeli government Ehud Olmert has advocated the return of virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the Jordanian, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, if peace with Palestine and Syria can be made in exchange for this.
He emphasized this in an interview printed Monday by the daily Jediot Achronot.
"We need to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means it becomes necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all," Olmert told the newspaper.
"We retain a certain percentage of these territories, but we will have to cede a similarly high percentage (Israeli territory) to the Palestinians, because there will be no peace without this," he added.
He acknowledged that a possible return would also include East Jerusalem.
"The one who wants safety in Jerusalem and, above all, doesn't want tractors or bulldozers to roll over his legs, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to do without part of Jerusalem," Olmert noted, alluding to two attacks in the city in July that killed several people and injured dozens of people.
According to the Prime Minister, it will be necessary to find a "special solution for the Temple Ber and sacred and historical places" that lie on the territory of the Old Town.
"The one who wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will have to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
That won't work," he reiterated.
Withdrawal from the Golan heights
Olmert advocated a withdrawal of Israel from the Golan Heights, which he believes is an indispensable condition for the conclusion of a peace treaty with Syria.
But this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"My proposal is not to make peace with Syria solely on the basis of a withdrawal from the Golan Heights," Olmert affirmed.
"The Syrians know all too well what they have to do without to get back the Golan heights.
They will have to renounce their current relationship with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with the (Shiite) Hezbollah movement; they will have to renounce the constant support they grant to the terrorism of the (Shiite) Hamas movement, the terrorist network Al-Khaida and the Jihad (the Holy War) in Iraq," the prime minister concretized.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India may cool down
If it fails to solve the problem with the Czech scientists charged in India with the unlawful collection of bugs, there could be some cooling of Czech-Indian relations, according to Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg.
