"If this does not clear up, then sure, then there will be a certain cooling," he explained after a meeting that took place on a Czech initiative.
Mukherdshi said after the talks that the executive branch could only intervene in judicial matters with difficulty.
Despite all this, he stated that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was acquitted of the indictment and received a fine, the central government wanted with the local government in Dardjiling, in whose jurisdiction the matter falls.
"His problem could be resolved," the minister said.
For Emil Kučera, who was sentenced to three years in prison, it would be Mukherdshi's view that he would appeal to a higher authority.
He could thus request release on bail and wait in freedom for his verdict, according to the minister.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner had also commented on negotiations.
"He recommends an appeal to a higher court, then a pardon would be in question for him," the head of Czech diplomacy said.
The only way the Czech side can intervene in the whole matter is to give the convict "competent legal support," the Indian minister cited.
At the same time, he said such help would already be offered to them by the Indian side.
"We have a great interest in maintaining good contacts with India that have a long-term tradition.
The Indians admit that," Schwarzenberg said.
At the same time, according to the Czech press agency ČTK, he reaffirmed the Czech Republic in front of its partner that the Czech Republic attaches great importance to the problem of Czech entomologists.
"We really consider it a big mistake to detain and accuse these Czech scientists," he explained.
A response to the question of whether he had received from the Indian side the commitment to deal with the matter, the minister dodged.
"I've already been promised quite a lot," he said.
Questions after the accident: Are stewards on the bus illegal?
The law does not know them, in a long-distance coach the walking is not allowed
In connection with the tragic accident of a student agency bus near the Italian Padua, the question arises whether stewards and travellers are allowed to walk back and forth while driving on the bus.
"If we wanted to strictly and formally comply with the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said the spokesman of the Ministry of Transport Karel Hanzelka.
The accident, which killed a twenty-two-year-old stewardess last week, was likely caused by the driver of the truck, who crossed the bus's path.
The young woman was sitting next to the driver in the least safe place in the car at that moment, although she had two more seats available.
However, a bus can also have an accident at the moment or brake sharply, in which the steward carries out coffee or newspapers.
A role also plays whether the bus is also equipped with standing places according to the vehicle letter.
If this is not provided on the bus, the travelers must sit.
Student Agency's long-distance coaches have no standing places; what the company's director, Radim Jančura, confirmed to Aktuálně.cz.
"We discussed this with the ministry, and this did not initially agree to the movement of travellers.
Later, this was withdrawn, and we reached a consensus that travellers would be allowed to go to the toilet while driving when they have their seat," he shared his point of view.
The law does not know a steward
"There is no clear legal interpretation for the role of a steward - no legislation describes this role.
However, there is also no legal provision that prohibits the carrier from providing services.
The law on road traffic only knows the term vehicle attendant; however, its rights and obligations it does not define," the spokesman for the Hanzelka ministry adds clearly.
The Director of the Road Vehicles Department of the Ministry of Transport Josef Pokorný, on the other hand, thinks that the law subsequently covers this issue.
"It depends on whether the bus also has standing rooms in the product approval.
That's all then," he insists.
Buses are divided into city buses, where there are standing rooms and the maximum speed is limited, local buses with standing rooms and a higher permitted speed and long-distance coaches without standing places with the highest permissible speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
As in the plane, says the expert
The BESIP specialist for road safety Jaroslav Hořín does not see a fundamental problem in the movement of stewards on board a bus.
"With a smooth driving style, there are not many dangers, the situation is comparable to the service on board an aircraft.
Again, it's not certain when turbulence will come, and the stewardess can bump its head."
"However, if a bus brakes sharply, then of course the laws of physics also apply.
Just like on a city bus or a tram.
The carrier must clarify the security of the stewards through internal regulations," he says, and also thinks that this problem will not be solved completely from the point of view of the law.
Jančura is ready to cancel the services
Student Agency is the only bus company to provide services from stewards.
The company employs about two hundred people in this role.
The director does not see her profession as risky even after the accident.
"But once I get the impression that the profession of steward is high-risk, I will delete it.
Coffee and newspapers can be given to travelers when boarding.
That would also cut costs," he said.
As an interest in security, the director of Asiana Alexej Litvin justifies the lack of stewards in his bus. His company operates only a fraction of lines compared to Student Agency.
"We don't have stewardesses, we've been fighting back from the beginning.
Sooner or later, this ends with some fatal accident," he had not quite a year ago for Týden.cz.
That was an incredible tragedy
In the accident of a scheduled bus to Naples, a young stewardess from the Pilsen region had crashed, who had worked for the company for two years.
The Slovenian truck had probably turned off the stand-off without blinking and had blocked the ride for the bus.
The driver of the bus tried to dodge through a sharp maneuver, but collided with the right front with the truck.
Jančura denies that the two places for the stewards had been sold.
"These places cannot be reserved on long-distance connections, they are blocked."
Company wants to sue truck drivers.
With compensation for the young woman's family, the agency will not wait for the court ruling, but she also expects financial damages from the guilty party.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
A more precise regulation of the movement of stewards on board a bus could bring a legal regulation, on which a thirty-member team of experts from the Ministry of Transport is already working for over a year.
"However, this has not yet reached a concrete conclusion.
Buses are also not necessarily on the agenda, rather the points system, the maximum speed on the highway and the use of mobile phones on the ride," according to expert Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not regard the activities of the stewards as something that could significantly endanger the safety of the passengers," Hanzelka said, with the control of the safety of the buses being the competence of the police and the occupational health and safety authorities.
A Czech judges the wrestling around the bottom of the sea
He approaches an electronic map depicting Australia and the adjacent sea areas.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but a small dot, lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia and together with it also the adjacent seabed.
The area is as large as the continent itself," said Italian lawyer Luigi Santosuosso, who is one of the thirty-member team of employees of the UN Division for Oceans and Maritime Rights.
His boss, the division director, the Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the interpretation and complements it on and to.
There is a work elan and enthusiasm here.
The bottom of the sea has so far had a little-known world rich in natural sources.
Here is oil, other ore and other non-renewable raw materials, but also previously unknown living organisms, which, for example, carry the key to the development of a drug against cancer.
A seabed, bigger than the mainland
The bordering states today vehemently registered their claim to the new sea areas.
According to a UN convention, they make use of their rights, on which they agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay in Jamaica.
It is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often reaches up to a few hundred kilometers from the shore of a country into the sea.
According to the Convention, this country has an exclusive right to all sources of the continental shelf.
"Simplified, as a continental shelf, the part of the seabed and its soles is considered, which is a natural continuation of the continent below the sea surface.
It crosses the borders of the shore sea, often the border of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone," explains Mikulka.
The request submitted by the relevant country to the Commission for the fixing of the external borders of the continental shelf must be submitted through extensive scientific and technical documentation based on many cost-intensive investigations and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
"One of our tasks is to provide legal and technical support to the Commission.
The Commission has so far negotiated five applications, namely from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the latter three countries have had success," Mikulka adds.
An international echo was recently met by the success of Australia, which was the first country to significantly increase its sea areas.
But New Zealand is also a winner - the expansion of the seabed, which was granted to the country by the Commission last week, is about 1.6 million square kilometers, about six times more than the size of the actual state.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in the investigations.
The gain that will flow to them in the future from the use of the seabed will, as they promise themselves, have invaluable value.
Other countries will also submit their applications gradually.
They can do this for ten years from the moment they ratify the "Montego Bay Agreement."
Where the continental shelf ends, the area of the ocean floor begins, which is described by the convention as the "common heritage of humanity."
There is no longer a state to hold a special position here.
The right to promote in this area is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"The seabed is not a gold-digging country," says Director Mikulka, adding that "individual areas are legally precisely defined and the system is contractually anchored."
Czechs in the Pacific
Some of the seabed now belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern Bloc within the framework of the joint organization "Interoceanmetal".
This received the status of a so-called "groundbreaking investor" in 1991 due to the convention, as well as the investors of a few other states.
The organization has the right to promote in the ClarionClipperton zone in the Silent Ocean between Mexico, Hawaii and Kiribati.
The area to be investigated by the investor is slightly larger than the former Czechoslovakia.
The seabed is located there, it is a kind of tatra on the seabed.
"You can promote there on a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area is a rich site of polymetal concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," according to another lawyer, the Indian Pakshi Rajan.
