Düsseldorf hopes rest on Frankfurt
There is no shortage of great words in the letter from the WestLB board to the employees of the house.
By combining units of the Düsseldorf financial institution with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank, "the central capital market house of the Sparkassen-Finanzgruppe" could be created, according to the letter announced on Monday.
WestLB would bring a "competence block" with sustainable earning power into such a business.
And in general, such a connection could be the decisive impetus for further bundling in the Landesbanken sector.
This is how it reads when a board wants to demonstrate capacity for action in a difficult time.
Because the ailing WestLB is still under enormous pressure.
Not only on the part of the EU Commission, but also by the Federal Financial Supervisory Authority, which has only recently made clear to the North Rhine-Westphalian state government, the time is urging to find a future solution.
However, there has been talk of a connection of a kind between the Deka bank, which savings bank customers know about because of their investment funds, and WestLB has been talking for some time - also on the Frankfurt side.
Although Deka-Bank CEO Franz Waas let it be known when presenting the half-year figures at the end of August, he sees no point in a merger of the house on the Mainzer Landstraße with a Landesbank, such as Helaba or WestLB.
But the Board of Directors of Deka, which is half supported by the Landesbanken and the Sparkassenverbanden, has commissioned the Executive Board to hold discussions with WestLB about joint business activities.
This could be about the capital markets business or parts of it.
Of course, the talks have only just begun, according to the financial centre.
Deka-Bank, which with its 3000 employees is one of the more important employers in the financial centre Frankfurt, is not for the first time when it comes to consolidation in the savings bank sector.
In 2003, it looked for a moment that Deka-Bank could merge with Landesbank Rheinland-Pfalz and Helaba.
However, this three-way covenant became nothing.
As soon as the plans had become public, the Hessian state government spoke out against the participation of Helaba.
The other two houses also did not find each other.
The Landesbank Rheinland-Pfalz went instead to the Landesbank Baden-Württemberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been mind games about a connection of Deka-Bank with Landesbanken.
Most recently, however, Günther Merl, CEO of Helaba, had spoken out against simulation games about going together with his house.
Regardless, however, the realization seems to mature that a move together of the various houses of the public sector does hardship.
After the state election in Bavaria is over, the first thing that could be a connection between BayernLB and the Landesbank Baden-Württemberg could move closer.
This is not necessarily good news for Helaba.
Should the pressure on further mergers increase, it gradually assumes the partners.
In the south, it would only be a junior partner, although it has so far endured the financial crisis far better than the houses in Munich and Stuttgart.
A merger with the West LB, in turn, the Sparkassen- und Giroverband Hessen-Thüringen, which holds an 85 percent stake in Helaba, pushed a bar earlier this year.
At best, the Nord LB would remain.
However, such geostrategic considerations are only one side.
On the other, it is a question of how the different business models of the individual houses fit together.
