Sleepless Nights for Creditors of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, German Finance Minister Peer Steinbrück emphasized only last week.
How good that the politician used the word "relative" and also invaded that the German banking sector would not be spared from the crisis-ridden developments.
Because it has now occurred on the weekend.
The Munich-based real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), listed in the Dax, receives a billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to shield itself from the turmoil in the markets.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that the loan assistance amounted to up to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate only has to pay interest on the part it also claims.
The money comes from both private and public banks.
The background is losses at the subsidiary Depfa.
The state financier had refinanced itself extremely short-term, according to a newspaper report for long-term projects for which he has lent money - which is no longer possible because of the mistrust in the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's cash reserve had shrunk by 95 percent to 2.37 million euros, and the equity ratio had also declined slightly from 1.6 to 1.45 percent.
Current income and net income from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared with the same period last year, income from attributions to receivables and certain securities, and from the dissolution of provisions in the credit business by more than 70 percent to 5 million euros.
Only thanks to higher income from refunds of downstream clearing costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group as well as from the reimbursement of interest according to the Fiscal Code and from the business provision for Group companies, the earnings reduction had still been moderate at around 16 percent.
After his privatization in 1990, the former state financier had initially speculated with commercial real estate loans, which had then been spun off in the Aareal Bank.
Because one earned too little in the classic state financing, the Depfa had then become increasingly involved in infrastructure projects and the financing of community projects of private investors and the state (private public partnership, PPP) and internationally diversified.
Hypo Real Estate now has to make depreciation and amortization on the value of the subsidiary, which will have a "substantial material effect" on the group's profit and loss account, it says quite indefinitely.
The fact is that the dividend has been cancelled.
It had already been cut by two-thirds for 2007.
Hypo Real Estate has been a major state and infrastructure financier since the Depfa takeover.
It is more dependent than other institutions on refinancing in the interbank market, as it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the American investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending among banks has again largely dried up, as the banks hoard their liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs short-term funds for refinancing annually for a part - around 50 billion euros - of Depfa's loan portfolio.
According to Hypo Real Estate, the Group's financing needs are covered by the loan for the foreseeable future and the company is shielded "from the influence of the currently largely incapable international money markets."
From other sources, it can be heard that thanks to the funds, the refinancing is secured until the end of 2009.
HRE CEO Georg Funke stated that Hypo Real Estate Group will no longer have to use the money markets for the foreseeable future.
Bundesbank and the Bundesanstalt für Finanzdienstleistungsaufsicht (BaFin) assume that the marketability of the Hypo Real Estate Group is now secured.
That stands to hope for shareholders and creditors of the bank.
But given the dynamics and uncertainties of the crisis, there is arguably no certainty.
