The swing-by is a flight maneuver of spacecraft, in which they receive additional momentum in the gravitational field of a celestial body, such as the Earth.
This allows the probes to save a lot of fuel.
The European-American research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick as well as the solar probe Ulysses.
What the researchers have been surprising for years, however, is that the missiles do not behave 100 percent in the way one would expect according to the time-honoured gravitational law.
Rather, there are irregularities in speed.
The probes are unexpectedly getting faster or slower.
