Addressing the Hispanic voters is a complicated task.
Barrack Obama's proposals on education are a typical example of this.
Obama's election campaign mentions that "the likelihood of African-American and Hispanic students successfully completing the school is lower than in white students" - which is true.
To close this achievement gap, Obama’s education plan specifically recommends, among other things, a bilingual transitional period in education for those who first learn English.
Still, the question to Obama is whether his commitment to bilingual education, which puts emphasis on teaching in languages other than English, contradicts his interest in reducing the distance in school performance.
Take, for example, "Sixth Street Prep," an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles.
The majority of students are Hispanic and come from low-income families.
More than a third of the students, many of whom have only recently been in the country, learn English.
Nevertheless, in 2008, an astonishing 100 percent of fourth-grade students passed the state exam in maths at a good level.
Also surprising, 93 percent of the children from the fourth school year were rated as good in the English exam.
This amazing success has been achieved with different methods than those favored by Obama.
The Sixth Street school puts its emphasis on review and practice, on steady control of knowledge and an attitude that tolerates no exceptions.
Furthermore, the school practices the approach according to which the training takes place in an English-speaking environment. That's exactly the point Obama should be aware of, according to headmistress Linda Mikels.
This approach attaches great importance to the almost exclusive use of the English language in specialist teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who rejects the idea of bilingual education, told me the school had a remarkable success with a student who had only just come from Mexico. 12 months later, you would be able to enter the classroom and no longer recognize it.
"It works," she noted, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like the "Sixth Street Prep" as a model for other schools with a large share of Latin American and other English-learning students?
The school's achievements would make the answer to this question easy, but the educational policy positions within his own party (the national educational associations have long supported the idea of bilingual education) and his own consistent support of bilingual education make predictions about Obama's answer uncertain.
While agreeing with the point that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the issue by noting that people should stop worrying about the legislation aimed at "only English."
Instead, he said, "you're supposed to make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Obama actually wants to close the performance gap, he should carefully consider educational models that work rather than despise and trivialize them.
