Hidden between the outgrowths of the theme parks around Orlando, a few miles from the glittering, loud and gigantic hustle and bustle, lies a quiet city where the pride and complications of African-American culture emerge.
Eatonville, the first entirely black city in the country and the hometown of Zora Neale Hurston, is no longer as easy to describe as Hurston did in 1935: "the city with 5 lakes, three croquet sites, 300 brown hides, 300 good swimmers, more than enough guavas, 2 schools and no prison."
