It is, on the one hand, a stronghold of literature and, on the other, an example of the - sometimes condemned, sometimes praised - black culture of the rural south that has its roots in American slavery.
It is not surprising that residents here are both proud and on guard.
And so really did the concerns about Eatonville's image actually start with Zora, as everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced the world to her hometown in books that came from the heart and were written in dialect, such as "Mules and Men" (1953) and "Their Eyes were watching God" (1973)
Five paragraphs in the Florida tour guide changed the city, which is very close to Route 77, a road that runs through the often-forgotten center of Florida, to the scenes of black history and human drama.
Cheeky like Oskar in both real life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clarke, and then turned to more private affairs.
"Away from the street to the left," she wrote, "is the brown --white painted modern school, with its manicured gardens and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, though he can barely read and write."
She also mentioned widow Dash's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of any kind and whatever-always suits hours rooms."
In just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, second marriage and sex.
This was certainly not a travel guide.
In fact, this was not a portrait that was appreciated by everyone.
"Zora described things as they were," according to 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of the Johnson girls who immortalized Hurston by quoting the men who sang songs about the her beauty, who were full of sexual allusions.
She added: "Some people didn't like this."
One still remembers Hurtson here as a lively eccentric who returned regularly after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that when Hurston came into town, she did so mostly without warning, in a noisy chevrolet, smoking and dressed in pants, in a city that itself is now imagining something on its venerable style of clothing.
According to Mr. Franklin, most of the inhabitants were fascinated, whereas many despised them.
"People were always glad to see Zora," Mr Franklin said.
But "she never stayed too long," he added while rocking in his chair, on a rear-facing terrace that looks out onto Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was in all likelihood baptized.
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books out of print.
Along with much of the world, Eatonville seemed to have forgotten them.
Although she was once a famous author, a contemporary Langstin Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an anonymous grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she lived.
There was no grand commemoration in Eatonville, no large-scale public readings.
"I don't think they understood their post in the world or their heritage in the slightest," according to Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography about Hurston released in 2003.
The turnaround came in the 1980s.
Orange County authorities wanted to put a five-lane highway through the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the municipality's slow two-lane main street.
Orlando's suburbs had already pushed Highway 4 through the western outskirts of the city.
The proposal was made when Eatonville was still recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among other things, had put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the fight against racial mixing brought hatred to the community.
"In that time, often a bunch of white boys came and they threw oranges and stuff at the off-seated people," Mr. Franklin said.
"There was even a woman who was killed.
They threw a watermelon out of the car.”
In 1955, in a letter to the Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand to force integration by describing its decision in the Brown case against the school board as "insulting rather than my race."
Residents today say that although the abolition of racial segregation was positive in some respects, it weakened the group cohesion in Eatonville and the self-confidence of its youth.
"Black children were used to being embraced - I remember - you hugged your teacher in the morning and you hugged his teacher in the evening," according to N. Y. Nathiri , daughter of Ella Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group for the protection of the Eatonville community.
That could be sustained for so long, she added, until teachers and students stopped coming from the same place.
"You didn't hug his white teacher, because he was a white teacher - I mean there's a cultural divide there," Ms. Nathiri said.
However, civil rights have helped create space for more Zora Neale Hurstons - black writers, actors and artists who override prejudice, just as she did, with positive self-confidence and statements like, "How can anyone refuse the joy of my society!
I don't understand."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker made her way to Hurston's nameless grave and began fighting for the revival of her fame.
Five years later, a much-praised Hurston biography was by Robert E. Finding Hemenway on the bookshelves, and made them a part of the American literary canon again.
The trunk road project came exactly at a time when Eatonville's most famous daughter was once again in the light of public view.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors saw her as a savior.
The municipality began planning a Hurston festival in 1988 to show what the district could destroy with the construction of the highway.
Thousands of fans came to the opening event two years later, and every January many return for the celebration.
A few years later, the district turned away from its road construction plans.
"The plans of a five-lane highway revived the city, accelerated the whole thing at top speed, evoked real citizen pride," Ms. Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd put it a little easier: "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory against the trunk road project has contributed to a change in the city's self-image.
There were more and more arrivals, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been going to church here since 1993, and locals began to reappreciate the past.
Eatonville was added to the statewide historic register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly cobbled and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Nowadays, Eatonville remains a special feature in Florida: just 6 miles from downtown Orlando, it can sometimes feel like a back alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded by only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(It is 90% black nowadays.)
Outsiders in search of the history of Eatonville and its significance are often still treated with caution.
For most interviews, a permit in advance is necessary and certain things - such as the wall painting of Eatonville's oldest church painted by a white man and depicting black men in fieldwork - must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms Jones, a brave, confident teacher with a fondness for dark red, still fear that their shielded community will be misunderstood.
And yet, at the same time that the Hurston festival grew up, an increased degree of homeland pride was also born.
Young people in particular tend to see Eatonville as Hurston saw their entire race: beautiful, with all its problems, neither worse nor better and just as proud, creative and hardworking, silly and mixed as any other racial and ethnic group in America.
It's the sincere love for this city that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in the city government or with the police, who, according to him, could use some help.
And even the younger ones, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon, eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park, have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people who just drive through here will think, "Oh, this city is nothing compared to all the others," Alondra Kenon said the other day on a Sunday after church.
"But when you actually stop and look at your story for a moment, it's a very beautiful city."
Here in New York, you can speak financial Latin fluently.
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If Manhattan tourists stayed away from the newspaper stalls and the massive television screens in Times Square, they wouldn't even realize they're in the middle of a debacle.
They would never believe that above their heads, in the shoebox-like offices with the glass facades, bankers and hedge fund managers who have the monopoly in New York, have daily the worst horror working day since the 1929 stock market crash.
Suppliers still push the metal tea trucks along sidewalks with loud rattles and carry trays loaded with muffins for the breakfast sessions.
Latinos still shuffled between apartments, like human pack animals loaded with around 50 ironed T-shirts hanging from a yoke-like bar lying on their shoulders.
Office workers are still waiting on their buffet stalls on their sidewalks and it is still impossible to get a yellow taxi on a weekday between 4pm and 7pm.
It didn't feel like a crisis at all until Thursday afternoon, due to all the doomsday talk, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had decided to put my compulsory process on the quiet late afternoon in my JP Morgan Chase regular branch, about 20 people were already in line.
Not at the money switches to withdraw or deposit money, but at the customer service counter where regular customers order checkbooks, ask tourists for directions to the department store Macy's and where new customers open accounts.
Most of them before me, I later learned from Starr, my "personal bank employee with a license," stood in line for the same reason as I did.
Unlike me, however, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, in places from where they commuted, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had withdrawn money from so-called thrifts (a little resembled a building society), cooperative banks and that local savings bank that have branches only in one state, and say they treat their customers like family.
Last year, 15 of these banks went quietly bankrupt.
Over the past few days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion assets, went into bankruptcy administration and when last Friday New Yorkers drove home over the weekend, was Wachovia, another bank that owns $440 billion worth of savings assets, in search of a saving buyer.
In fear of another collapse, the office and shop employees who stood before me brought their cash to a bank that is considered a safe haven, a bank responsible for most of the rescue purchases on Wall Street.
Normal New Yorkers have acquired fluent financial Latin in recent weeks.
A woman who was on the phone in my Chinese regular supermarket made so much familiarity with Lehman Brothers, the bankrupt bank and its emaciated-looking chief executive Dick Fuld, as if she were blaspheming about a rotten colleague.
And Lyn, the around 50-year-old uniformed concierge of my apartment block has strayed from our usual entertainment topics about Brad and Angelina and my food delivery.
"I now have all my savings in money market funds," she told me after my visit to the bank.
"I've changed, I don't take a risk anymore."
In memory of Vernon Handley and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's musical director since 1962, Vernon was "Tod" Handley (obituary on the 11th September) responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic and Choir.
As part of his music program for the city, he founded his great youth choir, Proteus, the following year.
It was intended for teenagers up to 21 years, but when the choir sang for the last time in 1979, some of us were already at the end of 20 - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological changer of forms) stood for the willingness and ability of the choir to tackle any piece of music presented to it, whether it was a madrigal or from the Messiah, whether a capella or with a full orchestra.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often amazing, always exciting and consisted solely thanks to the inspiration of that man and his enthusiasm for the music, which never let up for years.
How often did Tod think we were "let the music speak for itself."
He used to say, "The composer knows what he wants."
It's all in the music.
So it sings!"
His way of conducting was absolutely clear and precise, never bossy but also never exuberant.
Whatever the musical level, he always demanded an even higher level.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well over the last two decades, from 1962 to 1982, in which he ran the Guildford Philharmonic.
For the past 40 years, I have written reviews for over a hundred of his concerts and I can sincerely say that I was never disappointed by a single one - often I was inspired by them.
Death Handley was that rare combination of size and personal modesty.
He loathed conductors who, according to his words, simply "peddled with one or two well-known show horses in the world."
So many of us will miss him.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
In your obituary for William Woodruff (25. September) write that "in 1946 he resumed teaching economic history at Oxford and in 1950 received a Houblon-Norman research fellowship ... while at the same time he studied for a BSc, a MA and a doctoral degree.
This is a conclusion from an author's remark in Woodruff's book "Beyond Nab End," but it's not true.
From 1946 to 1953 he was a lecturer in economic history at the University of Nottingham and during this time he wrote a doctoral thesis on the British rubber industry under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers, which was later published in 1958 as "The British Rubber Industry".
He was a 1950-1951 in the United States in the wake of a Houblon-Norman scholarship, and spent the summer of 1952 at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953, he left Nottingham and went to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff wanted to cover up this part of his career.
Muslim graves desecrated during right-hand slide in Austria
Heinz-Christian Strache, a left-winger of Austria's right-wing Freedom Party, and Filip Dewinter, a member of Belgian right-wing Pertei Vlaams Belang, take on Thursday, the 17th. January 2008, at a demonstration in Antwerp to represent the organization "Cities against Islamization".
They wear signs in the style of traffic signs on which a mosque is depicted, crossed out with a red line.
Police accuse right-wing extremists of grave desecration at a Muslim cemetery in Austria, the same weekend on which far-right parties record significant gains in the country's general election.
In the night from Friday to this morning, more than 90 graves at the cemetery in Traun near Linz were severely damaged in an action organized, according to police.
The perpetrators sprayed Jewish symbols such as the David Stern on some of the graves, but crime investigators consider this an attempt to obscure the motive of extremists driven by hatred of Muslim immigrants.
It is not clear whether the incident is in any way related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said they were "deeply shaken" by the news of the grave desecration that was taking place as the Muslim Ramadan's religious month draws to a close.
At the same time, a round of conscience research is pending in Austria after the country slipped to the right in yesterday's parliamentary election.
The FPÖ and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, the two far-right parties that got almost 30% of the vote, campaigned in their election campaign for a strict anti-immigrant law and some of their election rulings were criticized by opponents as xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, chairman of the FPÖ, which won 18% of the vote, campaigned for a ban on headscarves and burqas and even made his aversion to food, which is generally associated with Islam.
At his last rally in Vienna, he spoke of a "European brotherhood" to prevent the growth of Islam.
Both parties want to ban the construction of mosques and minarets with the argument that these are political symbols of a continuous Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses conducted immediately after the election, which state that the far right is the politically strongest bloc in the country, suggest that this new development is based on young voters worried about their future in the European Union.
