`car bee' that avoids collisions
In order to promote the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature this time, more precisely, by the bees.
The Japanese company has developed a robot whose flight goes back to the swarming behaviour of bees and avoids accidents.
This robot is a bio-mimetic car robot drive or BR23C and represents the first step in the technologies for accident prevention.
The engineers from the technical development center of the Nissan Motor Co. have developed this small robot in cooperation with Research Center for Advanced Science and Technology of the renowned University of Tokyo (Japan).
According to Kazuhiro Doi, the head of technology PR and R&D brand management, the BR23C represents an extension of the four-layer Nissan safety shield.
This robot is designed to ensure that the cars of this brand are able to avoid the collisions.
During the flight, each bee builds up its own oval-shaped flight space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important are the facet eyes of the bee, which can see over an angle of 300 degrees in all directions, which allows it to fly undisturbed in their personal airspace without interruption.
In order to recreate the all-round perspective, the technicians developed the so-called Laser Range Finder (LRF).
He notices obstacles that are in front of the BR23C at a distance of up to two meters and are within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to a on-board microprocessor, which is directly translated into a signal for the avoidance of the collision
`The moment obstacle is noticed, the little robot will imitate the bee flight and immediately change direction by turning its wheels 90o or even larger angles to avoid the collision.
The biggest difference from other arbitrary systems is that this evasive maneuver takes place absolutely instinctively.
If it were not so, the robot might not be able to respond with sufficient speed to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, the director of the Mobility Laboratory and the senior engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deviate up or down, but neither can it move over; it can only move on two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in the infinite directions and in infinite ways the bees do.
For this reason, Nissan has used the rotation function in addition to acceleration and braking functions, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
`This device only requires every few seconds to process the information and to act according to this information.
It does not require the information or the intuitive logic of the maneuvers made, so it can continuously work with only a few dozens of KB of the storage space.
This sounds surprising, but it’s not about the GBs and not even the MBs of storage space.
This is the first step in the development of technologies for the immediate prevention of collisions, a technology that Nissan predicts to introduce in the next decade in the production cars.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than a variety of lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible application of this technology in the future could be the integration of the unit with a GPS navigation system by satellite to guide up to the destination when driving, avoiding the obstacles on the way.
