Hema-Quebec celebrated the 10th yesterday. anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, had every reason to rejoice, because Hema-Quebec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood banks in the world.
And above all, she has regained public confidence, which had been severely shaken by the scandal of contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves managed by the blood donation service of the Canadian Red Cross were contaminated with the HIV virus and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In light of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada launched a public investigation led by Judge Horace Krever in February 1994, which aimed to shed light on the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to draft policies to prevent a renewed catastrophe of this kind.
While Judge Krever was still reluctant to hand over his report, at the time several provinces set up a committee whose goal was to develop a new system for managing blood preserves in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
According to the reports of Gélineau and Krever, two blood banks were established in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which is responsible for Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Company to supply the other provinces and the two territories.
`1998, when Hema-Quebec started her work, barely 38% of people had confidence in the blood preserve system in Quebec, Dr. recalls. Décary.
The situation was daunting.
Through the enormous efforts to improve the safety of blood preserves and by working in this field during the following years, we have regained the public confidence," she says, before proudly stressing that by the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebec's population now had confidence in Hema-Quebec.
Dr. Décary, however, keeps in the awareness that `trust is something extremely fragile'.
Since its inception on 28. September 1998, Hema-Quebec acts on the principle of caution.
At that time, we witnessed the occurrence of numerous cases of human form of mad cow disease in Europe, a new species of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, tells this woman, who has been in charge since its foundation in 1998.
And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
So we invoked one of the main guidelines of the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which exclusion measures are applied if you do not know this and if a disease progresses only slowly, as is obviously the case with Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which manifests itself through degeneration of the brain, which inevitably leads to death.
So in April 1999, no blood was taken from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
Well, a few years ago it was proven without any doubt that this disease is transmitted via the blood.
Thus, this event has shown us that the principle of caution that we applied makes sense.
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: the nucleic acid tests (NST), which make it possible to detect the occurrence of the virus itself directly in the blood of the donor, and not that of the antibodies against the virus, as was the case with the tests used so far.
The NST made it possible to shorten the incubation time that takes place between the time the person was infected and the one when the first viruses can be detected by our techniques in the blood, the specialist explains.
This time could be reduced to a duration of less than a week.
So the risk that certain donors might be infected without knowing it, and you could not recognize this, was significantly reduced.
These improvements made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of transmitting AIDS via a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving blood infected with HIV.
In other words, this means that you would have to distribute 12 million blood preserves before someone would be infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood preserves each year, it would take more than 24 years before a case occurs in which HIV was transmitted via a blood preserve.
I believe that nowadays you can feel comfortable when you get a blood transfusion or prescribe it to restore health," says the head of the directorate of Hema-Quebec.
`Our challenge for the next ten years is to maintain the safety of our products.
