We have to monitor continuously," Dr. drives. Décary continued before stressing that in addition to secure care, Hema-Quebec must also provide adequate care.
“The demand is increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer-fighting treatments are more aggressive, patients often need new red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also affects the blood donor network, which on average only includes 3% of Quebec's blood donation-appropriate residents. '
Every healthy person who is 18 years of age or older and meets the aptitude criteria can donate blood every 56 days, i.e. six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who provide their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and those who have traveled to a country where malaria is spread is excluded from donating blood for a year.
`With these 3%, we manage to obtain an inventory that meets the needs of the hospitals.
