Free Opinion - The Orwellian Speech by Barrick Gold
In her issue of 17. In September, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Deputy Director General of the Canadian Gold Mine Barrick Gold.
This confirms, and pursues an Orwellian logic that the world's largest gold-making company sought a slander lawsuit over six million against three authors and a small penniless publishing house, with the aim of opening a `public transparent debate'.
If it is true that the judges are independent and impartial, then they do not judge the truth, especially not in the case of slander lawsuits, but about the law.
As expected, this fundamental difference was completely concealed by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to have a public debate is to ruin anyone who dares to represent one of their opposite opinions.
No matter how the trial goes, the authors and the editor of the book Noir Canada will have to spend significant sums to prepare their defense and fight with very unequal weapons against an army of lawyers paid out of the almost inexhaustible pockets of the gold mine.
The tactics in these unequal battles, by the way, are often to ruin the defenders to force a consensual settlement that silences the opposite side and also deters anyone who dares to deal with the question again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, she would have had to present her view of things before public opinion.
In contrast, what is common in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works is usually debated in Canada by the exchange of ideas rather than by stick blows.
It would therefore have been enough if the Goldmine had disclosed its books and files and opened a real debate, through the newspapers, media, publications and the financing of independent audit teams that could have brought light to this question.
But Barrick Gold doesn't seem to have confidence in public opinion and wipes aside the petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada with a hand movement.
Could perhaps Mr Garver explain how he can ask for a 'public' debate at the same time, and yet disregard the opinions of this very public?
Apparently, in the world of the Vice-President, this word encompasses only the generously paid lawyers, and not the community of all Canadians; a quite cramped view of the term.
In a democracy, even slanderers have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public, which supports the authors and editors of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it opposes the gold mine's brutal stance.
This public is willing to listen and judge Barrick, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, rather than in a framework that many perceive as a gag lawsuit (in the course of the `public debate', Barrick Gold has just made a demand to the authors of Noir Canada in which she requires them to stop using that term...).
Aside from Mr Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's lawsuit is a direct attack on freedom to academic research and truth-telling, which is fundamental to any democratic society.
It completely denies the right to cite credible sources and to discuss facts and interpretations that form the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible in a country like Canada to explore and discuss topics that do not please the rich companies of this world, who else can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have it by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
She has a right to answer.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to get a grip on debates and discrepancies and to resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's disproportionate lawsuit clearly shows that, contrary to what it dictates, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the university world, as well as for public debate, and it is time for governments to take action that restricts this kind of unjustified lawsuit.
