This criminal, stormy, violent and unforgettable boxer Rocky Graziano from Somebody Up There Likes Me (A Handful of Dirt) by Robert Wise, a role that was meant for James Dean, was resumed after his death and which Newman made known in 1956.
This sympathetic crook in the towering The Sting (Der Clou), which was awarded the Oscar for best film in 1973.
As a bitter and vengeful billiard player in the wonderful The Hustler by Robert Rossen (1961),
That face through the times, that was him.
Still him.
In his CV, epochs unite.
The youth know him mainly from the cult film Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), as Reggie Dunlop, the less orthodox coach of a hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the brothers Coen.
With a final role in 2003 as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Road to Perdition by Sam Mendes, the circle closed.
