What was produced in the invoice factory of Zuschlag &amp; Co.?
On 8. October begins negotiations in the criminal case against Jáno's contract and his accomplices.
In particular, the defendants are accused of involvement in organised crime, as well as grossly negligent damage and business fraud, and other criminal acts, including forgery of documents.
According to the public prosecutor's office, the funds lucrated from the tenders were used for their own purposes, while the services provided were often subject to fake invoices.
State funds and grants from the self-government - a total of HUF 65 million - are said to have partly flowed into the coffers of the organization Fiatal Baloldal, partly into the private coffers of individuals.
As the investigating authorities announced, fictitious invoices were submitted when receiving the tender funds, and the clubs are not said to have fulfilled their duties.
According to the indictment, much of the bills are said to have been forged.
The invoice blocks were bought on the market of Józsefváros, the round seals were made in Kiskunhalas.
The decision on which companies the invoices would be issued was decided on that round trip north of Lake Balaton to which István Lados was sent by János.
In the course of this "exploratory tour" Lados should locate pensions and restaurants.
He demanded bills on the consumption in order to be able to issue bills for the Ministry of Youth and Sport, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the self-government of Budapest, based on these templates.
These bills are said to have been manipulated by the majority of István Lados and his accomplice, András Őri, the latter according to our information being responsible for the constitution of the relevant reports.
One of the destinations of Lados' "exploration tour" was a beer restaurant.
As two invoices issued by Zuschlag and Co in 2003 can be seen, the restaurant company is said to have hosted the ninety-member group of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
Now, however, the boss of the company states that such a large group would not have fit into the restaurant at once.
Another invoice, issued in the summer of 2002 to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, later known as Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, also had serious form and content errors.
In a guesthouse in Badacsonytomaj, which has only three rooms and can accommodate no more than ten people at the same time, 130 guests are said to have stayed.
The imagination of the counterfeiters was apparently also unlimited when it came to the Pigal Kft., a restaurant, in whose accounting documents of the customers Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá do not even appear, according to the prosecution.
As Managing Director Győző Farkas told the hvg.hu, he was immediately aware that these were forged documents when documents were submitted to him by the public prosecutor's office during a questioning.
"Our company name and the tax number were incorrectly attached to the stamp."
And further: Apart from formal errors, the fact that the company is said to have accommodated one hundred people was also wrong, having a total of eleven rooms that could not possibly accommodate so many people.
Food was also mentioned on the bill, although the restaurant has not been in operation for a long time.
The busy counterfeiters have also failed to verify that the Budapest travel agency they targeted offers exclusively travel abroad, and so they have indicated Hungary trips on the cash bill, which also contradicted the company's accounting practice.
As was announced in the course of the investigation, they have also cited VAT on the invoices, although travel agency services relating to a country outside the EU are VAT-free.
The amount of VAT was incorrect in total on four invoices issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. to the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, since the company charges only 15 percent VAT instead of 25, and the employees issue only machine invoices, but the forged documents were handwritten.
Another mistake that the "invoice holders" had made was that they had indicated in one case "goods transport" as a service provided, although this is not offered by the company specializing in investment advice, the prosecutor's office said.
Other formal errors - incorrect invoice format, false stamp - were due to the fact that the one at Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, as well as to XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont could be exposed as counterfeit invoices.
Likewise, in the case of Ravenna Bt. and the Kunfehértó sports camp, whose managing directors claimed never to have issued the invoices.
Another "error" has been made by the counterfeiters at the HIB Kft. from Nyíregyháza: This company was in dissolution at the time (2001), when the group of the Fiatal Városért Egyesület is said to have eaten there - the mass administrator consequently stated that he had not issued the invoices himself.
Consciously fake
The other group of account managers are people who were well aware that they had to set fictitious invoices.
