The psychology of outbidding - or why we're willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overevaluate the file-off.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this well-known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people do not want to give themselves in a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even excessive prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers was to play the lottery, while the other participated in a playful action - in both cases, the active brain regions of the subjects were examined by means of functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to win money, but an increased activity of the striatum, a complex below the brain cortex, was measured in losers of the auction, in which the outbidding of the opponent plays an essential role.
Among many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore said that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an overreaction of the striatum.
In order to support their thesis, the economists in the research group have additionally conducted investigations to track the money.
In this case, three groups should bid against a partner under different conditions.
The control group was told the true value of the product, after which they made their stakes.
Another group was also promised 15 dollars reward in case they emerge as winners from the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which was also lost in the event of a lost game.
The difference between the two groups was therefore only that the emphasis on one was on winning, while the other was on losing.
As evidence of the hypothesis expressed by neurologists, however, the members of the group "against losing" were ready for higher stakes than those in the control or "profit" group.
"These results cannot be derived from any previous economic theory.
These have so far only justified the behaviors observed at auctions with the joy of winning or risk avoidance.
The contradiction between these two theories was resolved thanks to the imaging neurological procedures, so that we now have a third explanation ready," said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor to visit?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at a hundred thousand, but only seven thousand are treated, which is because the patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for infectious liver diseases triggered by various viruses.
The symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the pathogens and diseases differ from each other.
Depending on the pathogen, the hepatitis viruses spread in two different ways: in hepatitis A and E, the digestive tract (for example, contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D, the viruses can be transmitted through blood and other body fluids (such as sperm, vaginal secretions or saliva).
Travellers are recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B in any case, against the virus C there is no vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A are apparent about two-three weeks after eating the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by malaise, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that, jaundice occurs on the skin and in the eyes, the stool becomes light, the urine dark, and the recovery can last for up to two-three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million dies annually. People on the far more severe diseases triggered by hepatitis B, such as liver cancer and cirrhosis of the liver.
The main reason for this is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is in drug treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis of the liver and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, because the pathogen insidiously destroys the liver cells - in many cases, the first symptoms show up after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular check-ups, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those that underwent blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattooed people.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated to be 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult the family doctor at the first signs of unknown origin.
Recognized in time, the disease is curable, the virus can be eradicated, thereby banishing the risk of infection and preventing the development of cancer.
The 30. September is the World Hepatitis Day, held for the first time in 2004 by patient representatives worldwide.
The aim of the action is to raise awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their development and the importance of early detection.
