Are believers less in pain?
As recent research shows that religious faith acts as a kind of "painkiness" that is said to have already facilitated the death of Catholic martyrs.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment: it was investigated to what extent the belief in God affects the sense of pain of man, reported the British paper "Telegraph".
In the course of the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists each received electric shocks while studying a painting of the Mother of God.
As the results showed, the faithful were able to eliminate the bulk of the pain.
Using a brain scan technology, it could even be proven that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brains that is responsible for pain regulation.
The study was the first in a research project in which, in addition to scientists, philosophers and theologians from various departments of the university participate.
During the experiment, a sparkling device was tied to the left hand, which gave the electric shocks.
Participants were asked to focus heavily on two paintings: First, a picture of the Mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th. Century, and on the other hand Leonardo da Vinci's "Lady with the Ermine."
The researchers hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary among the faithful would provoke a kind of religious trance while choosing da Vinci's image because it was barely different from the other painting and perceived as soothing.
The subjects each spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received a total of 20 electric shocks in four stages, while they were to look at either the religious or the other painting.
Catholics reported that they felt "safe" at the sight of the Mother of God, as if they were "cared for," and they felt "rest and peace."
While viewing the religious painting, they reported over 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo's work in mind.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, said that similar effects could also be produced with other, strongly acting images in the atheists, one would only have to find the corresponding photo.
"We would have to find a picture that triggers very positive sensations, such as a mother or a father," the psychologist said.
Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and do so in many cases," Wright said.
After these excellent results, only the question remains what effect a Madonna picture of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the faithful.
Would the high-quality Virgin Mary achieve even better results?
