Intelligent car imitates the flight of the bumblebee
What would be the best way to develop new accident prevention technologies if not to imitate the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, those of the bees.
At CEATEC in Japan, an amazing project was presented in which the Nissan engineers were inspired by bumblebees in the creation of new accident-avoiding systems.
In collaboration with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C biomimetic system controlled by car robots, a mini-car equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area," which is very similar to our own "protective shield," Kazuhhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, said at the exhibition.
The composite eye of the bee, which can see in any direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
To mimic the function of the composite eye, the researchers took up the idea of the laser-controlled spacer.
This identifies obstacles before the BR23C in a field of view of 180 degrees within 2 meters, calculates their distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is registered in fractions of a second, and the car robot immediately changes course, similar to the movement of the bees, by turning the tires around the appropriate angle.
In contrast to previous systems, this maneuver takes place purely instinctively.
"If it weren't, the car robot could not react quickly enough to dodge the obstacles," explained Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the car robot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, as this technology corresponds to the innermost and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer within which accidents are currently still considered unavoidable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of bees when dodging other bees.
And that has to go in a split second.
However, unlike the bees, the dodging cannot be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the muzzle of the tires.
While the bees have endless possibilities to avoid other bees, the researchers were only able to use the rotational movement, or the acceleration and braking in the car robot.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient, and therefore have a longer lifespan than conventional lithium-ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it depends on the instinctive, intelligent response, and less on the processing of the data, and even less on the ability to store it.
This device only has to process a few inputs per second and react to them accordingly.
It does not have to store these, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction on the basis of previous maneuvers, so that it only takes up a handful of KB memory on an ongoing basis.
It doesn't require gigabyte- and megabyte-heavy memories.
This is the first step in the development of the immediate collision avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will be in production as standard within the next ten years.
Another application could find the technology in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately steering the driver around obstacles and thus guiding him to his destination.
