Fox in the chicken coop
Because of a person’s medication use, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign a contract with a customer.
Data protection experts fear the data market could become uncontrollable.
"There are privacy programs that couple the use of the drug data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
These should be in independent hands, otherwise we entrust the fox to the chickens," the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, developer of the prescription data tracking program.
Insurance companies determine the fees and the withdrawal amounts in the event of damage depending on the health status of the customer, and should the risk be assessed too high, the insurance is not taken out in the first place.
In the past, the customer was sent to a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only in the knowledge of the examination results.
Ten years ago, Dick invented a much cheaper method: Based on the customer’s identification number, he obtains the data of the last year and a half from the pharmacies, i.e. which preparations were purchased, and the program calculates from which disease the customer suffers and what his health status is.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it could be concluded that his blood fat level is untreatable, which would automatically rank him in a higher risk group.
There are several versions of the program in circulation - some even define a risk multiplier, so that the insurance companies only have to do the paperwork, but there are minor difficulties.
One of the disadvantages is that many medications can be taken for different purposes, such as migraines and hot flashes, but also against depression.
The latter is a high-risk factor from the point of view of the insurers, while the above-mentioned are not.
For the query and processing of the data, own companies have formed, which, before they obtain the data, ask the patient for his consent.
In the meantime, they have to do so by law, although omissions have not yet been punished.
Some companies even process the results of laboratory examinations and link them to the data on drug use. This provides an even more accurate picture of the patient’s health.
More and more companies are having access to the data, and the control of their use is becoming more difficult at the same time.
Although there is a separate data protection law for health data, its effect only extends to service providers in the health sector and insurance.
The bill has already been submitted to Congress, according to which the authorities could also control the data processing companies.
Dick Richard sees that this is too little, so he wants to further develop his program, so that the data can only be passed on with the consent of the person concerned.
Another question, of course, is that the person concerned can hardly prohibit access to his data, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
And so the chickens are quite somehow left to the fox's grace.
