Goodbye to the old Paradiso cinema – the cities close their historic cinemas
Historic cinemas are closing due to the beneficiary multiplex cinemas.
"A city without cinema halls is a blind city, like a face without eyes."
This picture by the director Giuseppe Tornatore describes with effect what is currently happening in the large urban centers of Italy, and also in the provinces.
The process of exclusion of cinemas, which began with the birth of the great multi-room complexes in the periphery, means death in the long run for the single-room cinema in the center. A process that not only seems inevitable and irrevocable, but also carries the features of a cultural crime.
Most of the time, historical places full of memories are affected, "it's like losing a friend with whom you have put a piece of street full of emotions back," according to the director of the film "Nuovo Cinema Paradiso," which earned him the Oscar and the Cannes Grand Prix 20 years ago. It is the story of a suburban cinema and its nostalgia, which consists of living in a forever lost cinema world.
The figures provided by the Anec, the central trade association, speak for themselves: in the last five years, the enormous amount of 316 traditional cinemas have had to close; these collierys mostly paid for the cinemas in the big cities: 10 in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the worst-hit regions are Emilia-Romagna with 82 lost cinemas, followed by Tuscany with 44 and Lombardy with 41.
This testifies to the fact that the main culprits are the multiplex cinemas, because it is precisely these three regions in which the largest number of these modern cinemas has been registered: with 195 in the last 5 years, Lombardy tops the lists, 81 are in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The business has developed in an irrational way," says Paolo Protti, the president of the Anec, "it is useful that new structures also emerge, but in the first place is the preservation of the already existing one, because if a hall in the city closes, not all its regular customers are ready to visit a multiplex cinema in the periphery instead of the old one.
And here remains the missing budget for the fund of the trade association outside eight: the debt burden recorded by the state is approx. 10 million euros.
It is a shame from the ethical-moral point of view that the government does not observe the existing laws.
To preserve the sector, between 16 and 18 million euros a year would be necessary."
