When the energy springs from the waves, suddenly the big ones run up
It is a non-swelling source of money that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and only now do the world's big energy companies seem to understand this.
Waves, currents and tides are the new renewable energy sources that everyone is now looking at, and also to occupy, such as giants such as Chevron.
The possibility of extracting energy from the movements of the sea has already been considered and investigated for 70 years; it is not by chance that these studies have intensified considerably since the first oil crisis.
When the price of oil collapsed around 1980, the idea of marine energy was gassed, but now the environmental organizations and the increased oil price are pushing for new stimulus in this sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimates that 15% of the world's energy demand could be met by the energies generated by the ocean waves.
This would be twice the energy currently produced by nuclear power plants.
In addition, there would be the currents and tides.
Giants in attack.
The first company to rely on marine energy is Enersis, which signed a contract in 2005 to build a power plant in northern Portugal.
When this news was published, it seemed to be a revolutionary step.
Two years later, there are now more and more companies from the traditional energy industry that rely on marine energy production.
"Chevron is investigating these technologies," he said, spokesman for a company known to the U.S. giant in the Wall Street Journal, and is weighing the opportunity to work with us."
It is about obtaining an approval from the American Energy Commission, which is necessary to start a project off the coast of Alaska.
This is a not to be underestimated sign, especially considering that oil is still being extracted by the US, especially in Alaska, and President Bush recently launched the plans for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, the companies Verdant Power Inc. from New York and Ocean Power from New Jersey, which invest in the new industry, are also not known, so observers speak of a rising interest.
Technologies that are still worth improvement.
Experts speak of a technology still on the rise, not least because the last doubts on the part of the environmentalists have not yet been clarified.
So far, projects such as those in Portugal and Scotland are of a rather small dimension and do not seem to cause any serious ecological problems.
However, in order to produce energy on a large scale, technologies with a far greater impact on the environment are needed.
There are different possibilities: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of connected buoys.
The thrust of the shafts, which moves the buoys up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure within the floats via pistons and cylinders.
This drives a turbine, which in turn operates a generator.
The electricity is sent to the coast via underwater lines.
So far, there are four planned plants of this kind, which are only waiting for the state approval. Some of the energy gained could also serve for military facilities.
Verdant Power, meanwhile, is already producing energy for a department store and a parking lot using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The water movements during the tides drive the turbines, which feeds the generator by the resulting rotational movement.
According to Verdant, a long queue of possible clients is already waiting for the necessary authorizations to use these energy sources.
First the waves, then the tides.
According to the Institute for Electricity Generation Research, the potential that is in the tides deserves a special interest at the moment.
Although it is also an irregular phenomenon, the tides are more predictable than wind currents, solar radiation and also waves, and therefore a more trustworthy source of electricity.
Especially the tidal energy is which states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, as well as other coastal states, have already invested 7.5 million dollars in 2008 – up to 35 million are already planned for 2009.
